TITLE: Amazon and E.U. Reach Deal to End Antitrust Investigation
SUMMARY: The online retail giant avoided a major fine but agreed to changes that have long been sought by merchants who depend on Amazon to reach customers.

TITLE: Clean Energy Quest Pits Google Against Utilities
SUMMARY: Google says it can’t meet its goals for renewable power unless state-regulated utilities, particularly in the Southeast, give way to market competition.

TITLE: Sam Bankman-Fried Said to Agree to Be Extradited to the US
SUMMARY: The disgraced FTX founder, who has been in a Bahamas prison for the past week, agreed to be sent to the United States, after a confusing day in court.

TITLE: Twitter Users Say Elon Musk Should Quit as Boss
SUMMARY: Mr. Musk had surveyed Twitter about whether he should remain in charge, and had said he would abide by the result.

TITLE: Ex-Google Contractor Settles Lawsuit Over Fellowship of Friends Sect
SUMMARY: The suit claimed that the Fellowship of Friends, an obscure group based in the Sierra Nevada foothills, gained influence inside Google.

TITLE: Wells Fargo to Pay $3.7 Billion Over Consumer Banking Violations
SUMMARY: The Consumer Financial Protection Bureau cited improper overdraft fees, account freezes, auto repossessions and misapplied home loan payments that have harmed millions of consumers since 2011.

TITLE: FTX Victims Face a Tough Road Getting Their Money Back
SUMMARY: The bankrupt crypto exchange owes billions to a long line of creditors. Getting their money back could prove difficult, given the unique nature of cryptocurrency assets.

TITLE: China’s Abrupt Covid Pivot Leaves Many Without Medicines
SUMMARY: Millions are desperate to get their hands on fever-reducing drugs and antivirals such as Pfizer’s Paxlovid as infections across China outpace supplies.

TITLE: How TikTok Became a Diplomatic Crisis
SUMMARY: A Chinese app conquered the planet — and now the U.S. is threatening to shut it down. Can the world’s biggest virality machine survive?

TITLE: Bank of Japan Surprises Markets With Policy Change
SUMMARY: The adjustment to bond buying policies was a rare move for the central bank, keen on helping the country battle rising inflation and a weak currency.

TITLE: Release of Trump Tax Returns Could Herald New Era for Taxpayer Privacy
SUMMARY: Revealing private documents risks a tit for tat with Republicans set to retake control of the House of Representatives.

TITLE: King Charles III Is the New Face of U.K. Money
SUMMARY: Pound notes with the new sovereign’s image will begin appearing in 2024, though money with his mother’s likeness will still be in circulation.

TITLE: Drew Griffin, CNN Investigative Journalist, Dies at 60
SUMMARY: His reporting on delayed care for military veterans at Veterans Affairs hospitals led to the resignation of the secretary of the department.

TITLE: Sam Bankman-Fried Is Expected to Agree to Extradition to the US
SUMMARY: The FTX founder, now in prison in the Bahamas, faces criminal charges that he engaged in widespread fraud since founding the cryptocurrency exchange in 2019.

TITLE: Epic Games, Creator of Fortnite, to Pay $520 Million Over Children’s Privacy
SUMMARY: The creator of Fortnite and other popular games violated children’s privacy and duped millions of users into unwanted purchases, federal regulators said.

TITLE: Tesla’s Direct Sales Model Helps It Thwart Customer Lawsuits
SUMMARY: Sales contracts prevent buyers of the company’s electric cars from pursuing class-action suits if something goes wrong.

TITLE: The Education of CNN’s Chris Licht
SUMMARY: The network’s chief executive knew the job would not be easy. But this hard?

TITLE: In the U.S., His Site Has Been Linked to Massacres. In Japan, He’s a Star.
SUMMARY: Hiroyuki Nishimura has become a famous voice for disenchanted young Japanese. What he talks much less about is his ownership of the notorious website 4chan.

TITLE: Elizabeth Warren Raises Questions About Elon Musk and Twitter
SUMMARY: In a letter to board, the Democratic senator asks whether the carmaker’s investors have been harmed by the billionaire tech mogul’s time running the social network.

TITLE: How FreshDirect Customers Took Reusable Bags and Made it Fashion
SUMMARY: When the grocery delivery company stopped taking back its bags during the pandemic, some people used their stashes to make purses, journals and works of art.

TITLE: Why It’s Hard to Predict What the Economy Will Look Like in 2023
SUMMARY: Years into the pandemic, it is still difficult to get a handle on what comes next for the economy by looking at examples from the past.

TITLE: Musk Asks Twitter Users If He Should Step Down After Fury Over His Policies
SUMMARY: Fury mounted over Mr. Musk’s moves to prevent Twitter users from sharing links to other social media platforms. The billionaire also asked whether he should remain as head of the service.

TITLE: 36 People Hurt, 11 Seriously, as Turbulence Rocks a Flight to Hawaii
SUMMARY: A 14-month-old and a teenager were among those injured in the flight from Phoenix to Honolulu, the authorities said.

TITLE: What AMC’s Streaming Troubles Say About the Greater TV Industry
SUMMARY: The company has struggled to earn enough from streaming to make up for losses from its traditional cable business. It is a story widespread in the industry.

TITLE: Streaming’s Golden Age Is Suddenly Dimming
SUMMARY: After years of breakneck growth, the number of scripted TV series orders made by networks and streamers is in decline.

TITLE: Twitter to Ban Accounts That Link to Social Media Rivals Like Mastodon
SUMMARY: The move may affect giant social media platforms, including Facebook and Instagram, as well as smaller ones like Mastodon and Truth Social.

TITLE: ‘Avatar: The Way of Water’ Has a Subdued Start at the Box Office
SUMMARY: Ticket sales totaled $134 million in North America, nearly doubling the opening for the first ‘Avatar.’ But Hollywood was expecting more.

TITLE: The Week in Business: The FTX Founder’s Rapid Fall
SUMMARY: Elon Musk suspends several journalists’ Twitter accounts, then reinstates them. The Fed is continuing to raise interest rates. And inflation is affecting the mind-set of holiday shoppers.

TITLE: Why Many Older Women Are Getting Pap Tests They Don’t Need
SUMMARY: Women over 65 are being screened for cervical cancer in diminishing numbers. But some are reluctant to give up the tests.

TITLE: Local News Outlet in New York Faces New Hurdle: A Declined Visa
SUMMARY: Phil O’Brien, a Briton who has run a Manhattan publication for several years, had his visa denied because immigration officials deemed his struggling business “marginal.”

TITLE: The Kroger-Albertsons Merger Spotlights a Popular Private Equity Tactic
SUMMARY: Albertsons wants to pay $4 billion to shareholders ahead of its proposed merger with Kroger, a move that would require the already debt-ridden company to borrow $1.5 billion.

TITLE: Twitter Reinstates Suspended Accounts of Several Journalists
SUMMARY: The brief bans, which came after Elon Musk had suggested the journalists were violating Twitter’s rules on personal privacy, had alarmed free-speech advocates.

TITLE: What Comes Next for San Francisco’s Emptied Downtown
SUMMARY: Tech workers are still at home. The $17 salad place is expanding into the suburbs. So what is left in San Francisco?

TITLE: U.S. Health Officials Seek New Curbs on Private Medicare Advantage Plans
SUMMARY: Proposed regulations would crack down on misleading ads for the private plans and would enhance scrutiny of denials for coverage of medical care.

TITLE: Restaurateur, Political Donor, Tipster: The Many Roles of FTX’s Ryan Salame
SUMMARY: The co-chief executive of an FTX unit who told regulators about wrongdoing at the exchange was a big Republican donor. He also bought restaurants.

TITLE: Elon Musk Flexes His Media Muscle by Suspending Reporters on Twitter
SUMMARY: Elon Musk’s moves this week set off a heated debate about complex issues of free speech and online censorship.

TITLE: Virtual Reality Pioneer John Carmack Is Leaving Meta
SUMMARY: John Carmack, who was chief technology officer of Oculus, which Meta bought, is departing the company.

TITLE: Biden Administration to Buy Three Million Barrels of Oil
SUMMARY: The move appears to signal an end to the government’s effort to sell oil from a strategic reserve to help tamp down energy prices, which soared after Russia’s invasion of Ukraine.

TITLE: GM Unit’s Self-Driving Taxis Are Subject of US Safety Investigation
SUMMARY: The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration is looking into unexpected braking by cars operated by Cruise, a part of General Motors.

TITLE: Starbucks Union Strikes at Dozens of Stores as Talks Stall
SUMMARY: Workers are pressing for a contract and accuse the company of anti-labor tactics. Management blames the union for the lack of bargaining progress.

TITLE: Elon Musk Faces Growing Anger Over Twitter Ban of Journalists
SUMMARY: The suspensions, which were criticized by U.S. and European lawmakers, could raise the regulatory heat on the social media platform — and Elon Musk’s other companies.

TITLE: Markets Extend Losses at End of Jittery Week
SUMMARY: Wall Street has been wary of the effects that central bankers’ determination to fight inflation could have on the economy.

TITLE: Forget Stock Predictions for Next Year. Focus on the Next Decade.
SUMMARY: Wall Street’s market forecasts for 2023 are worthless, our columnist says. But the long view is much clearer.

TITLE: Hardship 401(k) Withdrawals, Explained
SUMMARY: Most employers allow you to take funds out of your retirement account, but the withdrawals come with significant downsides. Our columnist discusses other options.

TITLE: Twitter Draws International Outrage for Suspending Journalists
SUMMARY: After Elon Musk’s Twitter suspends journalists, lawmakers and press freedom advocates fire back, threatening sanctions and fines.

TITLE: Can a Federally Funded ‘Netflix Model’ Fix the Broken Market for Antibiotics?
SUMMARY: Shortages and drug-resistant germs have renewed attention on a $6 billion proposal in Congress that would reconfigure the way antimicrobial drugs are developed and sold.

TITLE: Opposition to School Vaccine Mandates Has Grown Significantly, Study Finds
SUMMARY: A third of parents now feel they should be the ones to decide whether to get their children immunized against measles, mumps and other childhood diseases.

TITLE: Why FTX Is Anything But a Traditional Exchange
SUMMARY: FTX called itself an exchange. But it was vastly different from stock exchanges, which are highly regulated and barred from engaging in many of the activities FTX pursued.

TITLE: Twitter Suspends Half a Dozen Journalists’ Accounts
SUMMARY: The social media service, which is owned by Elon Musk, said that it suspends accounts that “violate the Twitter rules” but did not provide details.

TITLE: California Reduces Subsidies for Homes With Rooftop Solar
SUMMARY: The decision, which would reduce the incentive for homeowners to install solar panels, could influence other states to make similar changes.

TITLE: Frances Hesselbein, Progressive Leader of the Girl Scouts, Dies at 107
SUMMARY: Widely cited as a model of leadership, she took the scouts out of “the Betty Crocker era,” halting a membership decline and recruiting minority girls.

TITLE: Markets Drop as Investors Fear the Effects of Higher Interest Rates
SUMMARY: Central bankers around the world have pledged to continue raising interest rates even as economies slow.

TITLE: The US Imposes Sanctions on a Russian Oligarch and Other Officials
SUMMARY: The sanctions block financial transactions in dollars with Vladimir Potanin, the largest shareholder in Nornickel, the world’s biggest producer of palladium and refined nickel.

TITLE: Amazon to Publish the Next Tomb Raider Video Game
SUMMARY: The title will be the first major single-player game for Amazon. It is a coup for the retail giant, which has struggled to gain traction with its video game business.

TITLE: Amazon Agrees to Change Some Business Practices in EU Settlement
SUMMARY: The e-commerce giant avoided a fine, but will make a variety of changes regulators believe will help independent merchants who had raised alarms about Amazon’s tactics.

TITLE: Retail Sales Fell 0.6% in November, Despite Black Friday
SUMMARY: Inflation changed the way U.S. shoppers approached the holiday season, while lower gas prices and a decline in car sales were also factors.

TITLE: Elon Musk Sells Another $3.6 Billion in Tesla Stock
SUMMARY: Twitter’s owner has now sold $23 billion worth of Tesla stock this year, much of it after he pledged in April to stop selling shares to finance his deal to acquire the social media company.
